\begin_inset Formula $S_{7}$
\end_inset

 contains 504 elements of order 5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 The order of a permutation is the l.c.m.
 of its cycle lengths.
 Since 5 is prime, an element of order 5 must contain a cycle of length
 5.
 The two set members not in the cycle of length 5 must be fixed, because
 if they were together in a cycle of length 2, then the order of the permutation
 would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{l.c.m.}(2,5)=10$
\end_inset

, not 5.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So an element of order 5 amounts to choosing 5 members of a set of 7 (to
 participate in the 5 cycle), and an order in which to 
