\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are even permutations.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is an even permutation, because 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 can be written as a product of an even number of 2-cycles, so 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can be written as the same even number of 2-cycles (with the numbers in
 each cycle reversed).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can be written as an even number of 2-cycles by simply collecting the 2-cycles
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{-1}$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can both be written as evenly many 2-cycles, and the sum of even numbers
 is even.
\end_layout

