\emph on
Proposition
\emph default
.
 The set of odd permuations is not a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Suppose it were.
 Then it would have an identity.
 But the identity permutation is even (the product of zero 2-cycles).
 Contradiction!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, suppose it were.
 Then it would be closed under composition.
 But the composition of an even number of odd permutations is odd (because
 a composition can be written by collecting the cycles, and the sum of two
 odd numbers is an even number).
 Contradiction!
\end_layout

